This is the narrowest street in Paris with a width of only 1.8 meters. It has a funny name - the street of the cat who catches fish. According to legend, an alchemist lived here in the 15th century. And he always had a black cat with him, who could catch a fish in the Seine with one blow of his paw.  These days, of course, you won‚Äôt see a fishing cat anymore. The street is an ordinary narrow passage between houses. But if you walk past along the Seine embankment, you can stop by.

rue Cote-Rybalky is a street in the 5th arrondissement of Paris, connecting the Saint-Michel embankment and the rue Youchet. The street, 1.80 m wide and 29 m long, is considered the narrowest street in Paris (although this title is disputed by Sentier des Merisiers (fr. Sentier des Merisiers in the XII arrondissement) and one of the shortest). The street has been known since 1540. At that time, the embankment did not yet exist, and the street was an exit to the Seine. At first it was called rue des √âtuves ("Street of Steamers"), then the name changed to rue du Renard ("Fox Street"). According to one of the hypotheses, the name of the street comes from the sign of the store that was located on it. According to another urban legend, the black cat of Dom Perle, the owner of the fish shop located on this street, used to catch fish in the Seine with his paw.

It is the smallest street in Paris. As they say in other reviews, there is nothing special about it, it is dirty, but it must be said (that's why I put four stars) that since this street was all Paris. Napoleon Arto of the constant protests of the inhabitants of Paris and as can be seen by simply placing a table they blocked the streets preventing the soldiers from entering, ordered all the streets to be changed, tearing down the buildings and rebuilding new ones with wider streets. That is why this street is preserved as it was in Paris. Its appearance also recalls the hygiene of the time when waste was thrown out of the windows.

As soon as we arrived in front of the street, a very strong smell of urine invaded us and quickly made us not want to take any photo! We must stop praising this street as being an unusual place to do in Paris!!!
Officially the narrowest street in Paris, it is an authentic place where you really feel the past, you can easily imagine yourself being part of this era, all around many other streets full of charm.
